PSEUDOCODE
==========

Configure PA5 as output (LED)
Configure PC13 as input with pull-up (Button)

Configure EXTI:
    Route PC13 to EXTI line 13 via EXTICR
    Set falling edge trigger (button press = HIGH to LOW)
    Unmask EXTI line 13
    Enable EXTI4_15 IRQ in NVIC

Loop forever:
    Do nothing (WFI optional - sleep until interrupt)

EXTI4_15_IRQHandler:
    Check pending flag for line 13
    Clear pending flag immediately
    Small software debounce delay
    Toggle LED state via flag
    Drive LED via BSRR

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5   ->  Onboard LED (LD4)    - Active HIGH
PC13  ->  Onboard User Button  - Active LOW, falling edge triggers EXTI

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

EXTI (External Interrupt)
|-------------|--------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register    | Field  | Description                                                                          |
|-------------|--------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| EXTI->RTSR1 | bit 13 | Rising edge trigger enable for line 13. We leave this clear                          |
| EXTI->FTSR1 | bit 13 | Falling edge trigger enable for line 13. Set this - button press pulls line LOW      |
| EXTI->IMR1  | bit 13 | Interrupt Mask Register. Must be set to unmask (enable) line 13 interrupt            |
| EXTI->RPR1  | bit 13 | Rising edge Pending flag (G0-specific, replaces old PR register). Clear by writing 1 |
| EXTI->FPR1  | bit 13 | Falling edge Pending flag (G0-specific). Clear by writing 1 to acknowledge interrupt |
|-------------|--------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

SYSCFG / EXTICR
|---------------|-----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register      | Field                 | Description                                                                                             |
|---------------|-----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| EXTI->EXTICR4 | bits[15:8] for EXTI13 | Selects which GPIO port drives EXTI line 13. 0x02 = Port C. On G0, EXTICR lives inside EXTI, not SYSCFG |
|---------------|-----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

NVIC (Nested Vectored Interrupt Controller)
NVIC lives in ARM core. ISER (Interrupt Set Enable Register)
|------------|------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register   | Field            | Description                                                                                      |
|------------|------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| NVIC->ISER | bit for EXTI4_15 | Writing 1 to the correct bit enables the IRQ in the NVIC. EXTI4_15 is IRQ number 7 on STM32G071. |
|------------|------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY CONCEPTS
============

What is EXTI?
EXTI stands for External Interrupt/Event Controller. Its job is to watch GPIO
pins and detect electrical signal changes. A GPIO pin is just a wire. It carries
either a HIGH (3.3V) or LOW (0V) signal. EXTI watches that wire.

There are three types of changes it can detect:
* Rising Edge  - signal goes from LOW  -> HIGH
* Falling Edge - signal goes from HIGH -> LOW
* Both edges   - any change

When a physical event happens on a GPIO pin (like a button press), the CPU
doesn't see it directly. There is a pipeline it goes through:
Physical Pin -> EXTI -> NVIC -> CPU

Why Falling Edge for a button?
When the button is not pressed, PC13 sits at HIGH (3.3V) because of the internal
pull-up resistor we enabled. When we press the button, PC13 gets pulled to GND
(LOW). So the signal transition is:
Not pressed -> Pressed = HIGH -> LOW = Falling Edge

When EXTI detects the configured edge on a line, it raises a pending flag for
that line. Think of it as EXTI putting up its hand and saying "hey, something
happened on line 13!". Since we configured a falling edge, when the button is
pressed, bit 13 of FPR1 gets set to 1.

Even after EXTI detects an edge and sets the pending flag, it won't signal
anything further unless we unmask that line. Think of it like a Gate.

Every peripheral that can generate an interrupt is assigned an IRQ number
(Interrupt ReQuest number). This is ST's assignment, defined in the device
datasheet. The EXTI lines 4-15 all share IRQ7. This is why inside the ISR we
must check FPR1 manually to know which specific line fired, the NVIC only tells
the CPU "something in lines 4–15 happened", not which exact line.

On Cortex-M0+, ISER is a single 32-bit register covering all 32 IRQs, one bit
each. Writing a 1 enables it.

Full Flow - Here is what happens the moment we press the button (B1):
1. PC13 goes HIGH -> LOW  (falling edge)
2. EXTI Line 13 detects it (because EXTICR4 routes PC13 -> Line 13)
3. EXTI sets bit 13 in FPR1  (pending flag raised)
4. EXTI checks IMR1 bit 13 -> it's 1 (unmasked), so signal goes to NVIC
5. NVIC sees IRQ7 is active and enabled in ISER
6. NVIC interrupts the CPU, CPU looks up vector table slot for IRQ7
7. CPU jumps to EXTI4_15_IRQHandler()
8. Inside ISR:
   - we check FPR1 bit 13 to confirm it was line 13
   - we clear FPR1 bit 13 (write 1)
   - we toggle the LED
9. ISR returns, CPU resumes whatever it was doing (WFI sleep in our case)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Not clearing the pending flag, infinite ISR re-entry. If we enter the ISR and
  do not clear FPR1, the hardware sees the flag still set and immediately
  re-enters the ISR the moment it exits. The CPU gets stuck in an infinite ISR
  loop. Always clear the flag as the very first action inside the handler.

* G0 has RPR1/FPR1, not the old PR register. On STM32F4, the pending register is
  EXTI->PR. On STM32G0 it is split into two: RPR1 for rising edge and FPR1 for
  falling edge. If we copy code from an F4 example and use EXTI->PR, the address
  lands on SWIER1 and corrupt our interrupt config silently.

* EXTICR lives inside EXTI on G0, not SYSCFG. On most other STM32 families, the
  GPIO-to-EXTI mux is inside SYSCFG registers and requires enabling the SYSCFG
  clock via RCC->APBENR2. On G0 the EXTICR registers are part of the EXTI
  peripheral itself, no SYSCFG clock needed. This trips up anyone coming from F4
  examples.

* Debouncing inside an ISR is controversial. A blocking loop inside an ISR holds
  the CPU there and blocks all equal or lower priority interrupts. It works at
  this stage because we have only one interrupt. From Program 9 onwards the
  cleaner pattern is: set a flag in the ISR, debounce and act in the main loop.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* EXTI lines 4–15 share one IRQ on G0. On STM32G071, EXTI lines 4 through 15 all
  funnel into a single IRQ handler EXTI4_15_IRQHandler. If we have multiple pins
  on lines 4–15 triggering interrupts, we must check FPR1 or RPR1 inside the
  handler to figure out which line fired. Never assume, always check the flag.

* `__asm volatile ("wfi")` Wait For Interrupt puts the Cortex-M0+ into sleep
  mode. The CPU halts, clock gates partially, and power drops noticeably. It
  wakes the instant any enabled interrupt fires, in this case EXTI. Here it just
  keeps the main loop clean and saves a little power for free.

* IRQ priority on Cortex-M0+, M0+ supports only 4 priority levels (2
  bits). Priority is set via NVIC->IPR registers, 4 IRQs packed per 32-bit
  register, priority in the upper 2 bits of each byte. We leave priority at
  default (0 = highest) here. When multiple interrupts coexist in later
  programs, priority assignment becomes important.

* This program is the gateway, Every program from here on uses EXTI, NVIC, or
  both. The ISR structure, pending flag handling, and NVIC enable pattern
  established here are the same pattern we will use for TIM2 overflow
  interrupts, UART RX interrupts, DMA transfer-complete interrupts, and RTC
  alarm interrupts. The shape of the handler changes, the mechanism does not.
